sourceQuestion:
The following is an incomplete Pascal function to convert a given decimal integer (in the range -8 to 7) into a binary integer in 2's complement representation. Determine the expressions A, B, C that complete the program.

function TWOSCOMP(N: integer): integer;
var REM, EXPONENT: integer;
    BINARY: integer;
begin
  if (N >= 0) then BINARY := N
  else N := N + 16;
  EXPONENT := 1;
  TWOSCOMP := 0;
  while N <> 0 do
  begin
    REM := N mod 2;
    TWOSCOMP := TWOSCOMP + REM * [A];
    N := [B];
    EXPONENT := [C];
  end
end;

A. EXPONENT  B. N div 2  C. EXPONENT * 10

Which option correctly fills A, B, C?
A. A = EXPONENT, B = N div 2, C = EXPONENT * 10
B. A = 10, B = N mod 2, C = EXPONENT * N
C. A = EXPONENT * 10, B = N mod 2, C = EXPONENT
D. A = EXPONENT, B = N mod 2, C = EXPONENT * 10

